    "instruction": "Please load the four CSV files (metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, error_logs.csv) and produce a compact inventory summary for each file. For metric.csv: for each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute count of rows, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), global P95(value) and P5(value). Return the results sorted by count descending and limit to top 20 rows. For trace.csv: for each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute count, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), P95(value) and P5(value); sort by count desc and limit to top 20. For log.csv: for each unique (cmdb_id, log_name) compute count, min(timestamp), max(timestamp), P95(value) and P5(value); sort by count desc and limit to top 20. For error_logs.csv: return total row count, distinct cmdb_id list, earliest and latest timestamp overall, and up to 10 sample rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message). Also for each file return the overall total number of rows. Keep outputs compact and tabular (one table per file). Do not convert timestamps to datetime; keep timestamps as integers. Limit returned rows per table as specified." }

{
    "analysis": "Previous step collected a compact inventory of available telemetry: metric.csv (28,298 rows) and trace.csv (6,852 rows) contain dense per-minute series (~30–31 samples per group covering the investigation window), log.csv is sparse (~468 rows) but has per-component log counts and error_count (mostly zero), and error_logs.csv is empty. We therefore have sufficient metric and trace coverage to perform metric-based anomaly detection first (per rules). The next step is to detect metric anomalies within the reported incident window (2021-03-07 18:30 to 2021-03-07 19:00, UTC+8) using global thresholds (P95 and P5) calculated from the full series for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name). We will restrict metric anomaly scanning to the allowed root-cause components list (apache01, apache02, Tomcat01-04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02). From anomalies we will produce a compact ranked list of candidate component-KPI groups with counts, earliest anomaly timestamp, max/min in window, and a simple severity metric. This will narrow candidates for subsequent trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the entire metric.csv (do NOT filter by time before computing thresholds). Then filter metric.csv rows to the time window '2021-03-07 18:30:00' to '2021-03-07 19:00:00' (UTC+8). Restrict to rows whose cmdb_id is one of [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) group in that window, mark it anomalous if any row in the window has value >= global P95 OR value <= global P5. For every anomalous group produce one aggregated row with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count (number of rows in window breaching threshold), earliest_anom_ts (min timestamp of breaching rows), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, side (\"high\" if breaches are >=P95, \"low\" if <=P5, or \"both\"), severity (if side includes high compute max_value_in_window / p95, if side includes low compute p5 / min_value_in_window; if both report both ratios). Return up to top 20 anomalous groups sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity desc. Keep output compact and tabular and do not convert timestamps to readable datetimes." }

{
    "analysis": "Previous executor run produced a broad list of 20 anomalous (cmdb_id,kpi_name) groups in the incident window; however most are constant-zero series where global P95 and P5 are 0.0, producing spurious 'both' breaches and infinite severities. Per the diagnosis rules we should ignore constant/zero-value KPIs (non-informative) and focus on KPIs with actual variation or nonzero thresholds to find real faults. The next step is to re-run the metric anomaly detection but filter out constant-zero series (or where global P95 and P5 are both zero and window max==min), and then report remaining candidate groups with their breach counts, earliest breach timestamp, and a bounded severity metric (e.g., ratio to threshold when threshold>0). Also report how many groups were excluded as constant-zero so we know if metrics are informative.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 on the entire series. Then filter rows to the incident window 2021-03-07 18:30:00–2021-03-07 19:00:00 (UTC+8) and to components in [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each group compute: anomaly_count (rows in window with value>=p95 OR <=p5), earliest_anom_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, side ('high'/'low'/'both'), and severity_ratio defined as: if side includes 'high' and p95>0 then max_value_in_window / p95 else if side includes 'low' and p5>0 then p5 / min_value_in_window else NULL. Exclude groups where (max_value_in_window == min_value_in_window) AND (p95 == 0 and p5 == 0) as constant-zero non-informative. Return: (a) a table of the remaining anomalous groups (limit 20 rows) sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc; (b) a single-row summary with counts: total_groups_scanned, anomalous_groups_found, groups_excluded_constant_zero. Keep outputs compact and do NOT convert timestamps to datetimes." }

{
    "analysis": "Metric-level anomaly scan produced many spurious hits: large number of constant-zero series (403 groups) and many groups whose window values equal their global thresholds (side='both') so severity is not meaningful. That means metric signals in metric.csv are largely non-informative for pinpointing a single failure in the incident window. According to the diagnosis workflow, next we should use traces to localize the root cause among services (especially when metric signals are ambiguous). trace.csv has dense coverage (30 samples per trace group) and contains service-to-service durations and row_count metrics (examples: trace.self.duration_mean, trace.to_Tomcat01.duration_mean, trace.to_Tomcat01.row_count). We will compute global thresholds (P95/P5) per trace group using the full trace.csv, then detect anomalies in the incident window (2021-03-07 18:30:00–19:00:00 UTC+8). We will exclude constant series and return a compact ranked list of anomalous trace groups with earliest anomaly timestamp and a bounded severity metric to identify candidate faulty services or call links. This will narrow downstream candidates for final localization via logs/metrics.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the entire trace.csv (do NOT filter by time before computing thresholds). Then filter trace.csv rows to the incident window 2021-03-07 18:30:00–2021-03-07 19:00:00 (UTC+8). Restrict cmdb_id to the root-cause candidate list [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) group in the window compute: anomaly_count (rows where value >= p95 OR value <= p5), earliest_anom_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, side ('high'/'low'/'both'), and severity_ratio defined as: if side includes 'high' and p95>0 then max_value_in_window / p95 elif side includes 'low' and p5>0 then p5 / min_value_in_window else NULL. Exclude groups where (max_value_in_window == min_value_in_window) AND (p95 == 0 and p5 == 0) as non-informative. Return: (a) table of anomalous trace groups (limit 20 rows) sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc with the columns above; (b) a single-row summary with counts: total_trace_groups_scanned, anomalous_trace_groups_found, groups_excluded_constant_zero. Keep output compact and do NOT convert timestamps to datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "We used metric-level anomaly scanning but found many non-informative constant series and ambiguous 'both' breaches, so metrics alone do not give a clear, single faulty component. Trace-level anomaly scanning produced clearer candidates: anomalous trace groups concentrate on MG01 and MG02 interactions (several trace.from_* and trace.to_* duration_p95 and row_count groups) and also some IG and Tomcat trace groups. The trace anomalies have non-zero variation and earliest_anom_ts values (examples: MG01 trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95 earliest 1615113000, MG01 trace.from_dockerA2.duration_p95 earliest 1615113120). To localize the root cause we must find which component shows the earliest fault across all traces in the incident window and then inspect its downstream callers/targets. The next step is therefore to compute, per component (cmdb_id), the earliest anomaly timestamp among trace groups (using global P95/P5 thresholds computed on the full trace series, excluding constant-zero non-informative groups), plus counts of anomalous trace groups per component and the top anomalous trace names with their earliest breach times and breach side. This will identify the earliest faulty component and the precise occurrence timestamp to inspect logs/metrics for reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P5 over the entire trace.csv. Then filter trace rows to the incident window 2021-03-07 18:30:00–19:00:00 (UTC+8) and to the allowed component list [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each (cmdb_id,trace_name) in the window mark anomaly rows where value >= p95 OR value <= p5; exclude groups where (max_value_in_window == min_value_in_window) AND (p95 == 0 and p5 == 0). Then produce a compact per-component table with columns: cmdb_id, earliest_anom_ts (minimum timestamp among all anomalous rows for that component), anomalous_trace_group_count (number of distinct trace_name groups for this component that had any anomaly in the window), and top_anomalies (for up to top 5 trace_name groups for that component list trace_name, earliest_anom_ts_for_that_trace, side). Sort the per-component table by earliest_anom_ts ascending and return all rows (limit 20). Also return a single-row summary with total_trace_groups_scanned, total_components_with_trace_anomalies, groups_excluded_constant_zero. Keep outputs compact and do NOT convert timestamps to datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold metric scans and trace-level anomaly scans. Metrics were noisy: many constant-zero or threshold-equal series produced spurious anomalies and were excluded. Trace analysis is more informative: MG01 and MG02 show the largest number of anomalous trace groups and have earliest anomaly timestamps at the start of the incident window (1615113000). Several MG01/MG02 trace.*.duration_p95 and trace.*.row_count groups breached global thresholds starting at 1615113000–1615113120, making MG01/MG02 the highest-priority suspects. To localize the root cause component and reason we need to (a) inspect MG01/MG02 resource KPIs (metrics) during the incident window for real resource issues (CPU/memory/JVM/disk/network) and (b) check logs for error patterns. error_logs.csv is empty, so log.csv is the next source. The immediate next action is to analyze metric.csv specifically for MG01 and MG02: compute global thresholds from the full metric series (P95/P5), filter to the incident window, exclude constant-zero groups, and report anomalous KPIs with earliest anomaly timestamp, breach side, and a bounded severity metric. This will indicate whether MG01/MG02 exhibit resource faults (e.g., high JVM memory, OOM, high CPU) that could explain the trace anomalies.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. Compute global P95 and P5 for every (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full file. Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2021-03-07 18:30:00–19:00:00 (UTC+8) and to components MG01 and MG02 only. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) group in the window determine: anomaly_count (rows where value >= p95 OR value <= p5), earliest_anom_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, side ('high'/'low'/'both'), and severity_ratio defined as: if side includes 'high' and p95>0 then max_value_in_window / p95 elif side includes 'low' and p5>0 then p5 / min_value_in_window else NULL. Exclude groups where (max_value_in_window == min_value_in_window) AND (p95 == 0 and p5 == 0). Return a compact table of anomalous MG01/MG02 KPI groups (limit 20 rows) sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc, and a one-row summary with counts: total_MG_groups_scanned, anomalous_groups_found, groups_excluded_constant_zero. Keep outputs compact and do NOT convert timestamps to datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have run metric and trace anomaly scans. Metrics were noisy and many KPI groups were constant or equal to their global thresholds, producing ambiguous 'both' breaches with undefined severity. Trace analysis provided a clearer signal: MG01 and MG02 have the largest number of anomalous trace groups with earliest anomaly timestamps at the start of the incident window (1615113000), making them the highest-priority suspects. To decide whether MG01 or MG02 is the root cause and identify the exact occurrence time and reason, we must inspect logs for MG01/MG02 during the window (since error_logs.csv is empty). Logs may reveal errors or evidence of resource problems (OOM, GC, network errors) that explain trace anomalies and point to the precise occurrence timestamp. Therefore we should query log.csv for MG01 and MG02, computing global thresholds per log_name from the full file, then aggregating windowed stats for MG01/MG02 groups (counts, earliest nonzero error timestamps, min/max values in window, and global p95/p5). This will reveal whether MG logs show error spikes or informative patterns aligning with trace anomalies.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv. For every unique (cmdb_id, log_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the entire log.csv (do NOT filter by time). Then filter log.csv to the incident window 2021-03-07 18:30:00–19:00:00 (UTC+8) and to components MG01 and MG02 only. For each (cmdb_id,log_name) group in that window compute: count_in_window, min_timestamp_in_window, max_timestamp_in_window, global_p95, global_p5, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, earliest_nonzero_value_ts (the minimum timestamp in the window where value>0, or NULL if none). Exclude groups with zero rows in the window. Return: (a) a table of these MG01/MG02 log groups limited to top 20 rows sorted by count_in_window desc; (b) a one-row summary with total_log_rows_scanned, total_MG_log_groups_in_window, and total_MG_log_rows_in_window. Keep outputs compact and do NOT convert timestamps to datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "We queried metrics, traces, and logs. Metrics were noisy: many KPIs are constant or equal to their global thresholds causing ambiguous 'both' breaches. Trace analysis pointed to MG01 and MG02 as the highest-priority suspects: they have the most anomalous trace groups and earliest anomaly timestamps at the start of the incident window (1615113000). Log-level evidence for MG01/MG02 is absent in log.csv and error_logs.csv. To determine the root cause component and exact occurrence time we need to see which MG metric(s) actually show extreme absolute values (e.g., very high memory %, high JVM memory usage, high CPU, disk, or network metrics) during the window rather than rely on degenerate threshold-equals. A focused metric table for MG01 and MG02 within the window sorted by maximum observed value will reveal which resource(s) are most stressed and give candidate earliest timestamps to tie to trace anomalies. This is the next logical atomic step toward root cause localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. Filter rows to cmdb_id IN [MG01, MG02] and to the incident window 2021-03-07 18:30:00–19:00:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: count_in_window, min_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, mean_value_in_window, earliest_ts_of_max (minimum timestamp where value == max_value_in_window), global_p95, global_p5 (computed over the full metric.csv for that group, i.e., do not compute p95/p5 after filtering). Exclude groups with zero rows in the window. Return a table sorted by max_value_in_window descending, limited to top 20 rows. Keep output compact and do NOT convert timestamps to datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metrics, traces, and logs. Trace anomalies concentrate on MG01 and MG02 with earliest trace anomalies at the start of the incident window (1615113000). Metric inspection of MG nodes shows both MG01 and MG02 have large JVM heap metrics; MG02 HeapMemoryUsed reached 1.227316e+09 (global P95=1.103706e+09) with earliest max at 1615114620, while MG01 HeapMemoryUsed reached 1.058360e+09 (global P95=1.016732e+09) with earliest max at 1615113600. To decide the root cause we need the precise first time each MG node crossed its global P95 and whether those breaches form a sustained fault (consecutive minutes). The prior outputs gave max timestamps but not the earliest breach times or consecutive-breach durations. Determining earliest breach and consecutive duration for the critical HeapMemoryUsed KPI on MG01 and MG02 will let us (a) pick which component first entered a fault state and (b) assess severity (max / p95). Logs for MG nodes are empty in the window, so metrics + traces are our primary evidence.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) over the full file. Then filter metric rows to the window 2021-03-07 18:30:00–19:00:00 (UTC+8) and to the two groups: (MG01, JVM-Memory_7779_JVM_Memory_HeapMemoryUsed) and (MG02, JVM-Memory_7779_JVM_Memory_HeapMemoryUsed). For each group compute: global_p95, max_value_in_window, earliest_ts_of_max (min timestamp where value==max), earliest_breach_ts (minimum timestamp in window where value >= global_p95), anomaly_count_in_window (number of rows in window with value >= global_p95), consecutive_breach_length (the length in minutes of the longest consecutive run of rows in the window starting at earliest_breach_ts where value >= global_p95), and severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95. Return a compact two-row table (one row per group) with these columns. If a group never breaches p95 in the window, set earliest_breach_ts and consecutive_breach_length and anomaly_count_in_window to NULL/0 accordingly. Keep output compact and do NOT convert timestamps to datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds, detected anomalies in metrics and traces, filtered out constant/degenerate series, and focused on MG01 and MG02 because trace anomalies concentrated there. Metric inspection showed both MG01 and MG02 briefly exceeded their JVM HeapMemoryUsed global P95 during the incident window: MG01 earliest breach at 1615113240 (severity ~1.04x P95) and MG02 earliest breach at 1615113720 (severity ~1.11x P95). Trace anomalies for MG nodes appeared earlier (many trace groups flagged from 1615113000), and MG02 has slightly more anomalous trace groups (42) than MG01 (39). Logs are absent for MG nodes in the window, so we rely on trace+metric correlation. At this point we still have two plausible candidate root components (MG01 and MG02). To choose the root cause component and the precise occurrence time we need a compact cross-evidence summary per MG node combining: (a) number of anomalous trace groups and earliest trace anomaly timestamp, (b) number of metric KPI groups that breached global thresholds in the window and earliest metric-breach timestamp among those groups, and (c) the maximum metric severity ratio observed (to prefer the node with larger deviation). This will let us pick the predominant faulty node (per rules: predominant nodes with most faults, and the one with the largest deviation if same level).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Produce a compact two-row summary for MG01 and MG02 combining trace and metric anomaly evidence. Using previously computed global thresholds (P95/P5 on full series), filter the incident-window rows (2021-03-07 18:30:00–19:00:00 UTC+8). For each component (MG01 and MG02) compute: component, trace_anomalous_group_count (number of distinct trace_name groups in the window with any anomaly), earliest_trace_anom_ts (min timestamp among those anomalous trace rows), metric_anomalous_group_count (number of distinct kpi_name groups in the window with any value >= global P95 OR <= global P5, excluding constant-zero/non-informative groups), earliest_metric_breach_ts (min timestamp among metric rows breaching global thresholds), and max_metric_severity_ratio (max over their metric groups of severity defined as group max_in_window / group_p95 when p95>0). Return a two-row table (one row per component) with these columns. Limit output to these two rows and keep it compact. Do NOT convert timestamps to datetimes." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds on full series, performed metric anomaly detection, then trace anomaly detection, and narrowed candidates to MG01 and MG02. Trace anomalies cluster on both MG nodes with earliest trace anomalies at 1615113000. Metric evidence shows brief HeapMemoryUsed breaches on both MG nodes: MG01 first breached P95 at 1615113240 (severity ~1.04x) and MG02 first breached at 1615113720 (severity ~1.11x). Combined counts: MG02 has slightly more anomalous trace/metric groups overall while MG01 has the single largest metric severity ratio (2.0 on some metric). Logs for MG nodes are empty in the window, so we must rely on traces and metrics. According to the localization rules, when multiple same-level components are faulty, we should use traces to find the most downstream faulty component in call chains (the last faulty service/container appearing in traces). Therefore the next concrete step is to inspect the anomalous trace groups for MG01 and MG02 and determine for each trace whether it represents traffic \"to_*\" (outbound from the component), \"from_*\" (inbound to the component), or \"self\", and to extract the peer service/container name and earliest anomaly timestamp. This will let us see whether MG01 or MG02 appear as downstream (callee) or upstream (caller) in the anomalous call chains and thus identify which MG node is the likely root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv (global P95/P5 already computed previously), select anomalous trace groups for cmdb_id in [MG01, MG02] within the incident window 2021-03-07 18:30:00–19:00:00 (UTC+8). For each anomalous (cmdb_id, trace_name) produce one row with: cmdb_id, trace_name, direction (set to 'to' if trace_name contains 'to_', 'from' if it contains 'from_', 'self' if it contains 'self', else 'other'), peer (the substring following 'to_' or 'from_' up to the next '.' or end, e.g., 'Tomcat01' or 'dockerA1'; empty for 'self' or 'other'), anomaly_count (number of rows in the window breaching global threshold), earliest_anom_ts (minimum timestamp of those breaching rows). Sort results by earliest_anom_ts ascending then anomaly_count desc. Limit output to top 50 rows. Return the compact table only." }

